{"title_page": "Changi Airport MRT station", "text_new": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox station\n| background = \n| name = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Changi Airport\n  | zhname = \u6a1f\u5b9c\u673a\u573a\n  | taname = \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\n  | msname = Changi Airport \n  | line = EAST WEST\n  | line2 =\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n  | terminicode = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 3.png|25px]] \n}}\n| type = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit (MRT)]] station\n| image = File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Platform A.jpg\n| image_caption = Changi Airport station platform level\n| address = 70 Airport Boulevard<br />Singapore 819661\n| coordinates = {{Coord|1|21|26.54|N|103|59|19.81|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}\n| other = [[Changi Airport Bus Terminal]], Taxi\n| structure = Underground\n| platform = 2 ([[1 island platform]])\n| depth = \n| levels = 1\n| tracks = 2\n| parking = Yes ([[Changi Airport]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]])\n| bicycle = Yes ([[Changi Airport]])\n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = {{start date and age|df=yes|2002|02|08}}\n| opening = {{start date and age|df=yes|2040}} ([[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]])\n| closed = \n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = Yes\n| ADA = Yes\n| code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n| owned = \n| operator = [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (East West and Thomson\u2013East Coast lines)\n| zone = \n| former = \n| services = {{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|branch=Changi|previous=Expo|''Terminus''}}\n| mpassengers = \n| map_locator = {{Superimpose| base = MRT map EW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = East West line\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Changi Airport MRT station\n | x = 224\n | y = 69\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Changi Airport MRT station (CG2)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) station and the eastern terminus of the [[East West MRT line|East West line]]'s Changi Airport Branch. The station is located in [[Changi]], [[Singapore]], within [[Singapore Changi Airport]], and is built in an East-West direction with the two ends of the station connecting directly to Changi Airport Terminals 2 and 3. It is also one of the few stations, where faregates are on the same level as the platforms. It is currently the easternmost MRT station in Singapore until the planned opening of [[Aviation Park MRT station]] in 2029.\n\nDuring the construction of Terminal 3, ideas had been put forth to build a new branch line connecting to and around the airport. The current two-station branch line was finalised in 1996 and construction started in 1999. The station opened on 8 February 2002, with passenger demand lower than expected. Nevertheless, it has provided a new transport option for the airport, benefitting both Singaporeans and tourists. On 25 May 2019, it was announced that the station will be incorporated as part of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]], connecting to Terminal 5 by 2040.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-stations-tel-extension-and-possible-new-rail-line-lta-2040-blueprint|title=New MRT stations, line extensions and a possible new rail line: LTA's 2040 blueprint|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Changi MRT.JPG|left|thumb|Changi Airport MRT station, featuring flight information box in addition to train route information]]\n[[File:CG1 changi airport faregates.jpg|left|thumb|Changi Airport is one of the few stations where faregates are on the same level as the platforms.]]\nBefore the MRT line, Changi Airport had been operating with no [[Airport rail link|rail link]] and with full reliance on [[Taxicabs of Singapore|taxi]] and [[Bus transport in Singapore|bus connections]] since the airport began operations in 1981. This has proven effective given the short 20 kilometre distance to the city via the [[East Coast Parkway]] and affordability of taxis and buses. Public buses instead link commuters to nearby MRT stations at [[Bedok MRT station|Bedok]], [[Tampines MRT station|Tampines]] and [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]]. Therefore, there were previously unsuccessful attempts to propose an extension to Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT Link to Airport: Not in next 10 years|date=17 May 1991|work=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=No MRT Line to Changi yet|date=20 March 1992|work=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of extending the Mass Rapid Transit system to Changi Airport was reconsidered when Terminal 3 was being built.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT extension to airport reconsidered.|date=2 August 1994|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The earlier plans had long been made for a new line branching off from the existing [[East West MRT line|East West line]] at [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Next Stop:Changi Airport?|date=2 August 1994|work=The New Paper}}</ref> with some conceptual plans showing a tentative route alignment up to the airport along Airport Boulevard, continuing beyond the airport to Changi Point, before turning southwest back towards the city along the east coast of the island. The plans were finally announced by then [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] on 15 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore Mass Rapid Transit Employees' Union (SMRTEU)'s annual Dinner and Dance  |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1996111503/lhl19961115s.pdf |website=NAS |accessdate=10 July 2019 |date=15 November 1996}}</ref> However, the route alignment showed a deviation from previous plans. The final plan involved building only the first two stations, namely [[Expo MRT station|Expo]], and the Changi Airport station, the underground station built between Terminal 2 and [[Changi Airport Terminal 3|Terminal 3]]. The alignment of the station at the airport has been switched perpendicularly to an east\u2013west direction, such that the station leads to two of the terminals directly from either end of the station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19961212-1.2.51.7 |title=MRT Line will not go beyond passenger terminals |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=12 December 1996}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=changi+airport+mrt&KA=changi+airport+mrt&DF=02%2F01%2F1990&DT=01%2F09%2F2010&Display=0&NPT=&L=English&CTA=Article|title=Changi Airport MRT line details|date=12 December 1996|work=The Business Times|access-date=}}</ref> As part of the President's Challenge 2001, a part of a charity walk goes through the tunnel between Expo and Changi Airport stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Lim|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Chairty walk to talk place underground|date=12 August 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Perfectly legal, and for a good cause!|date=9 September 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Terence|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Tunnel walk a hit|date=9 September 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nThe Contract 504 for the construction of Changi Airport MRT station and its associated tunnels was awarded to Kumagai-Sembawang Joint Venture in October 1998. This project was a joint effort which combines Japanese technology and experience with local knowledge of subcontractor availability, supplier availability, due to the challenges of the construction of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.jsce.or.jp/jsce/open/00035/2001/56-cs/56-cs-0266.pdf|title=Underpinning Works in Construction of MRT Changi Airport Station in Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A groundbreaking ceremony was held on 29 January 1999. In the speech by then-communications minister [[Mah Bow Tan]] at the ceremony, he highlighted the challenges of the construction of the station, which requires close cooperation between various parties such as the [[Land Transport Authority]] (LTA), the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore]] (CAAS) and the contractors. For the construction of Changi Airport station, different methods of deep excavations using various ground support systems were adopted. The construction work involved the challenge of deep excavation works right next to nearby developments such as the existing Terminal 2 structures.<ref name=\"Excavations\">{{Cite book|last=Murugamoorthy|first=C.|title=Behaviour of Various Support Systems for Deep Excavations, Changi Airport Underground MRT Station|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In addition, closing monitoring is needed for the construction of the {{convert|1|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} tunnel leading to the station, which goes directly underneath the runway and airport terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1999012901.htm|title=Speech By Mr Mah Bow Tan, At The Changi Airport Line Ground Breaking Ceremony, 29 Jan 99, 10 am, Singapore Changi Airport|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During the construction, [[CPG Corporation|CPG Consultants]], which was designing Terminal 3 at the time, provided 20 staff to complement the LTA team on the Changi Airport line extension.<ref name=\"CPG consultants\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpgcorp.com.sg/cpgc/Project/Project_Details?ProjectID=1312|title=CPG Consultants - Changi Airport Mass Rapid Transit Station (MRT)|website=www.cpgcorp.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nThe station opened on 8 February 2002,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Completion%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension/|title=Completion Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Airport MRT stop to open tomorrow|date=7 February 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with the official opening ceremony of the Changi Airport MRT extension conducted on 27 February 2002.<ref name=\"Speech 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension%20on%2027%20February%202002/|title=Speech By Mr Yeo Cheow Tong At The Opening Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension on 27 February 2002|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since the station's opening, passenger traffic has been moderate, as most bus routes were maintained and continue to be a popular means of cheap, direct transport for local airport/airline employees, as well as travellers not living along the East West line. Many air travellers also prefer to continue taking taxis or private transport as not all of the MRT services have luggage racks in the trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Chew|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Taxi still the way to go for Changi air travellers|date=26 August 2002|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> However, taxi drivers claimed that the station have actually put them at a disadvantage, reporting a loss of 20 percent in earnings. By then, there are about 20,500 commuters travelling the station daily.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phei Phei|first=Leong|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20020311-2.2.4.11?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article&QT=changi,airport,station&oref=article|title=Airport woes for cabbies|date=11 March 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial numbering of the station was EW29, but was changed on 20 June 2003 to CG2.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=What SMRT said earlier|date=8 August 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Incorporation into the TEL===\nOn 25 May 2019, the [[Land Transport Authority]] announced an extension of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]] (TEL) to Changi Airport.  Set to be completed by 2040, The TEL will be extended from its current terminus at [[Sungei Bedok MRT station]] to serve the future Changi Airport Terminal 5, and the stretch between Tanah Merah and Changi Airport, which is currently part of the East-West line, will be transferred over to the Thomson\u2013East Coast line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents===\n*On 24 July 2002, a glass panel of the atria wall shattered. The area was quickly closed off, but train services were not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=24 July 2002 |publisher=[[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]] |access-date=16 January 2018 |quote=At 12.05pm, a piece of tempered glass at the atria wall in the Changi Airport MRT Station shattered into small fragments. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135244/https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |archive-date=16 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Joint%20Press%20Release%20By%20Land%20Transport%20Authority%20And%20Singapore%20MRT%20Ltd%20Atria%20Wall%20In%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station/|title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\n*On 24 September that year, a man died at the station, apparently having fallen five stories from the departure hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20030925-2.2.11.1|title=Man Dies at Changi Airport|date=25 September 2003|work=TODAY}}</ref>\n\n*On 17 January 2020, the rail operator SMRT said that it had found a crack in the crossing at Changi Airport MRT Station, found during inspection works in the morning. Trains have to be diverted to only one platform and have to travel at a slower speed as they approach the affected crossing.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/slower-train-service-changi-airport-mrt-station-until-jan-21-after-crack-spotted-track|title=Slower train service to Changi Airport MRT Station until Jan 21, after crack spotted on track|date=17 January 2020|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Station details and design==\n[[File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Exit A.jpg|thumb|The panes of the glass atria walls seen from Exit A leading to the station|left]]\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{MRT color|East west}}\n|legend =track\n|map=\nuSTR!~MFADEg\\uSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to {{mrts|Expo}}\nuSTR\\uSTR\nudSTRc2!~uvABZg2-\\d!~uv-ABZg3\\udSTRc3\nudABZg+1\\udSTRc14!~d-BS\\udABZg+4\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nudSTR\\dBS-\\udSTR\nuENDEe\\uENDEe\n}}\nVarious features have been incorporated into the design to make the station aesthetically pleasing to travellers.<ref name=\"Speech 1\"/> The station is designed by architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]], featuring a large interior space and a {{convert|150|metre|ft}} linkbridge spanning over the platform, connecting Terminals 2 and 3 with travellators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgtrains.com/network-ewl.html|title=East-West Line|website=SGTrains|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Engineering company Meinhardt also provided structural design engineering of the glazing system and the tensioned cable structure of the two atria (approximately 60m long by 20m wide by 36m high each) located at both ends of the station box adjacent to Terminal 2 and 3 of Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meinhardt.com.sg/projects/changi-airport-glass-atria/|title=Changi Airport Glass Atria {{!}} Meinhardt \u2013 Transforming Cities, Shaping the Future|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nChangi Airport station is currently served by the [[East West MRT line|East West line]], which connects to the airport from [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah station]] as a shuttle service. Initially, after the station was first opened, there were through services from [[Boon Lay MRT station|Boon Lay station]] to this station.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boon Lay to Expo: MRT now running|date=20 December 2001|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> However, due to low ridership, the route reverted to being operated as a shuttle service from 22 July that year, with trains from Changi Airport station terminating at Tanah Merah station instead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Board MRT to airport from Tanah Merah.|date=18 July 2003|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The first train from Changi Airport station departs at 5.31 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.59 am on Sundays instead, with the last train from the airport departing at 12.06 am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Changi Airport)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> From Tanah Merah station, the first train towards the station departs at 5.20 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.47 am on Sundays instead, with the last train towards the airport from Tanah Merah station departing at 11.50 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/tanah-merah/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Tanah Merah)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Headway]] between trains varies from 7 \u2013 9 mins during peak hours, and 12 mins during off-peak hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/|title=Changi Airport MRT Station {{!}} Land Transport Guru|date=2018-01-31|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the future, the station will be served by the TEL as part of the TEL extension to the airport.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Changi Airport MRT Station}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/ChangiAirport.aspx}}\n* [http://blog.smrt.com.sg/?p=159 Official blogsite]\n* [http://www.mynetbizz.com/MRT/To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/HarbourFront-To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station.cfm HarbourFront to Changi Airport MRT station route]\n* [http://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/ Changi Airport MRT Station]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|east-west=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Changi Airport MRT station}}\n[[Category:Changi]]\n[[Category:Airport railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2002]]\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Singapore]]\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 350268 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 61111 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 403 us -->\n\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 6083007 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73546 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 925 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 338330 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 60129 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 416 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 410717 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73630 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 861 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 321675 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 56806 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 409 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n", "text_old": "{{short description|MRT station in Singapore}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox station\n| background = \n| name = {{SMRT Infobox Colour\n  | enname = Changi Airport\n  | zhname = \u6a1f\u5b9c\u673a\u573a\n  | taname = \u0b9a\u0bbe\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe\u0ba9\u0ba8\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\n  | msname = Changi Airport \n  | line = EAST WEST\n  | line2 =\n  | line3 =\n  | code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n  | terminicode = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 3.png|25px]] \n}}\n| type = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit (MRT)]] station\n| image = File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Platform A.jpg\n| image_caption = Changi Airport station platform level\n| address = 70 Airport Boulevard<br />Singapore 819661\n| coordinates = {{Coord|1|21|26.54|N|103|59|19.81|E|type:railwaystation_region:SG|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=SMRT|line=East West}}\n| other = [[Changi Airport Bus Terminal]], Taxi\n| structure = Underground\n| platform = 2 ([[1 island platform]])\n| depth = \n| levels = 1\n| tracks = 2\n| parking = Yes ([[Changi Airport]], [[Jewel Changi Airport]])\n| bicycle = Yes ([[Changi Airport]])\n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| opened = {{start date and age|df=yes|2002|02|08}}\n| opening = {{start date and age|df=yes|2040}} ([[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]])\n| closed = \n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = Yes\n| ADA = Yes\n| code = {{SMRT code |CG|2}}\n| owned = \n| operator = [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]]) (East West and Thomson\u2013East Coast lines)\n| zone = \n| former = \n| services = {{S-rail|title=SMRT}}{{S-line|system=SMRT|line=East West|branch=Changi|previous=Expo|''Terminus''}}\n| mpassengers = \n| map_locator = {{Superimpose| base = MRT map EW.svg\n | base_width = 300px\n | base_caption = East West line\n | float = Red Dot.svg\n | float_width = 5px\n | float_caption = Changi Airport MRT station\n | x = 224\n | y = 69\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Changi Airport MRT station (CG2)''' is an underground [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] (MRT) station and the eastern terminus of the [[East West MRT line|East West line]]'s Changi Airport Branch. The station is located in [[Changi]], [[Singapore]], within [[Singapore Changi Airport]], and is built in an East-West direction with the two ends of the station connecting directly to Changi Airport Terminals 2 and 3. It is also one of the few stations, where faregates are on the same level as the platforms. As the only MRT Station to serve the Changi planning area, it is currently the easternmost MRT station in Singapore until the opening of the [[Aviation Park MRT station]] in 2029.\n\nDuring the construction of Terminal 3, ideas have been put forth to build a new branch line connecting to and around the airport. The current two-station branch line was finalised in 1996 and construction started on 1999. The station opened on 8 February 2002, with passenger demand lower than expected. Nevertheless, it has provided a new transport option to the airport. On 25 May 2019, it was announced that the station will be incorporated as part of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]], connecting to Changi Airport Terminal 5 by 2040.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-mrt-stations-tel-extension-and-possible-new-rail-line-lta-2040-blueprint|title=New MRT stations, line extensions and a possible new rail line: LTA's 2040 blueprint|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Changi MRT.JPG|left|thumb|Changi Airport MRT station, featuring flight information box in addition to train route information]]\n[[File:CG1 changi airport faregates.jpg|left|thumb|Changi Airport is one of the few stations where faregates are on the same level as the platforms.]]\nBefore the MRT line, Changi Airport had been operating with no [[Airport rail link|rail link]] and with full reliance on [[Taxicabs of Singapore|taxi]] and [[Bus transport in Singapore|bus connections]] since the airport began operations in 1981. This has proven effective given the short 20 kilometre distance to the city via the [[East Coast Parkway]] and affordability of taxis and buses. Public buses instead link commuters to nearby MRT stations at [[Bedok MRT station|Bedok]], [[Tampines MRT station|Tampines]] and [[Pasir Ris MRT station|Pasir Ris]]. Therefore, there were previously unsuccessful attempts to propose an extension to Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT Link to Airport: Not in next 10 years|date=17 May 1991|work=The Straits Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=No MRT Line to Changi yet|date=20 March 1992|work=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of extending the Mass Rapid Transit system to Changi Airport was reconsidered when Terminal 3 was being built.<ref>{{Cite news|title=MRT extension to airport reconsidered.|date=2 August 1994|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The earlier plans had long been made for a new line branching off from the existing [[East West MRT line|East West line]] at [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Next Stop:Changi Airport?|date=2 August 1994|work=The New Paper}}</ref> with some conceptual plans showing a tentative route alignment up to the airport along Airport Boulevard, continuing beyond the airport to Changi Point, before turning southwest back towards the city along the east coast of the island. The plans were finally announced by then [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] on 15 November 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore Mass Rapid Transit Employees' Union (SMRTEU)'s annual Dinner and Dance  |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1996111503/lhl19961115s.pdf |website=NAS |accessdate=10 July 2019 |date=15 November 1996}}</ref> However, the route alignment showed a deviation from previous plans. The final plan involved building only the first two stations, namely [[Expo MRT station|Expo]], and the Changi Airport station, the underground station built between Terminal 2 and [[Changi Airport Terminal 3|Terminal 3]]. The alignment of the station at the airport has been switched perpendicularly to an east\u2013west direction, such that the station leads to two of the terminals directly from either end of the station.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19961212-1.2.51.7 |title=MRT Line will not go beyond passenger terminals |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=12 December 1996}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=changi+airport+mrt&KA=changi+airport+mrt&DF=02%2F01%2F1990&DT=01%2F09%2F2010&Display=0&NPT=&L=English&CTA=Article|title=Changi Airport MRT line details|date=12 December 1996|work=The Business Times|access-date=}}</ref> As part of the President's Challenge 2001, a part of a charity walk goes through the tunnel between Expo and Changi Airport stations.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Lim|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Chairty walk to talk place underground|date=12 August 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Perfectly legal, and for a good cause!|date=9 September 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Tan|first=Terence|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Tunnel walk a hit|date=9 September 2001|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\nThe Contract 504 for the construction of Changi Airport MRT station and its associated tunnels was awarded to Kumagai-Sembawang Joint Venture in October 1998. This project was a joint effort which combines Japanese technology and experience with local knowledge of subcontractor availability, supplier availability, due to the challenges of the construction of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.jsce.or.jp/jsce/open/00035/2001/56-cs/56-cs-0266.pdf|title=Underpinning Works in Construction of MRT Changi Airport Station in Singapore|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A groundbreaking ceremony was held on 29 January 1999. In the speech by then-communications minister [[Mah Bow Tan]] at the ceremony, he highlighted the challenges of the construction of the station, which requires close cooperation between various parties such as the [[Land Transport Authority]] (LTA), the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore]] (CAAS) and the contractors. For the construction of Changi Airport station, different methods of deep excavations using various ground support systems were adopted. The construction work involved the challenge of deep excavation works right next to nearby developments such as the existing Terminal 2 structures.<ref name=\"Excavations\">{{Cite book|last=Murugamoorthy|first=C.|title=Behaviour of Various Support Systems for Deep Excavations, Changi Airport Underground MRT Station|publisher=Land Transport Authority|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In addition, closing monitoring is needed for the construction of the {{convert|1|km|mi|adj=mid|-long}} tunnel leading to the station, which goes directly underneath the runway and airport terminal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1999012901.htm|title=Speech By Mr Mah Bow Tan, At The Changi Airport Line Ground Breaking Ceremony, 29 Jan 99, 10 am, Singapore Changi Airport|website=www.nas.gov.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> During the construction, [[CPG Corporation|CPG Consultants]], which was designing Terminal 3 at the time, provided 20 staff to complement the LTA team on the Changi Airport line extension.<ref name=\"CPG consultants\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpgcorp.com.sg/cpgc/Project/Project_Details?ProjectID=1312|title=CPG Consultants - Changi Airport Mass Rapid Transit Station (MRT)|website=www.cpgcorp.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\nThe station opened on 8 February 2002,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Completion%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension/|title=Completion Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Airport MRT stop to open tomorrow|date=7 February 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> with the official opening ceremony of the Changi Airport MRT extension conducted on 27 February 2002.<ref name=\"Speech 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20The%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Extension%20on%2027%20February%202002/|title=Speech By Mr Yeo Cheow Tong At The Opening Of The Changi Airport MRT Extension on 27 February 2002|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Since the station's opening, passenger traffic has been moderate, as most bus routes were maintained and continue to be a popular means of cheap, direct transport for local airport/airline employees, as well as travellers not living along the East West line. Many air travellers also prefer to continue taking taxis or private transport as not all of the MRT services have luggage racks in the trains.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seng Kim|first=Chew|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=Taxi still the way to go for Changi air travellers|date=26 August 2002|work=The Straits Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> However, taxi drivers claimed that the station have actually put them at a disadvantage, reporting a loss of 20 percent in earnings. By then, there are about 20,500 commuters travelling the station daily.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phei Phei|first=Leong|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20020311-2.2.4.11?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article&QT=changi,airport,station&oref=article|title=Airport woes for cabbies|date=11 March 2002|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial numbering of the station was EW29, but was changed on 20 June 2003 to CG2.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Search?ST=1&AT=advanced&K=Changi%20Airport%20Station&KA=Changi%20Airport%20Station&DF=01%2F04%2F2001&DT=01%2F08%2F2003&Display=0&NPT=&L=&CTA=Article#|title=What SMRT said earlier|date=8 August 2001|work=The New Paper|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Incorporation into the TEL===\nOn 25 May 2019, the [[Land Transport Authority]] announced an extension of the [[Thomson\u2013East Coast MRT line|Thomson\u2013East Coast line]] (TEL) to Changi Airport.  Set to be completed by 2040, The TEL will be extended from its current terminus at [[Sungei Bedok MRT station]] to serve the future Changi Airport Terminal 5, and the stretch between Tanah Merah and Changi Airport, which is currently part of the East-West line, will be transferred over to the Thomson\u2013East Coast line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=de83f659-4b0d-4609-840e-3deb3ac9b4b9|title=Land Transport Master Plan 2040: Bringing Singapore Together {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents===\n*On 24 July 2002, a glass panel of the atria wall shattered. The area was quickly closed off, but train services were not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=24 July 2002 |publisher=[[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]] |access-date=16 January 2018 |quote=At 12.05pm, a piece of tempered glass at the atria wall in the Changi Airport MRT Station shattered into small fragments. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116135244/https://www.mot.gov.sg/News-Centre/News/2002/Joint-Press-Release-By-Land-Transport-Authority-And-Singapore-MRT-Ltd-Atria-Wall-In-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/ |archive-date=16 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Joint%20Press%20Release%20By%20Land%20Transport%20Authority%20And%20Singapore%20MRT%20Ltd%20Atria%20Wall%20In%20Changi%20Airport%20MRT%20Station/|title=Joint Press Release By Land Transport Authority And Singapore MRT Ltd Atria Wall In Changi Airport MRT Station|website=www.mot.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\n*On 24 September that year, a man died at the station, apparently having fallen five stories from the departure hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20030925-2.2.11.1|title=Man Dies at Changi Airport|date=25 September 2003|work=TODAY}}</ref>\n\n*On 17 January 2020, the rail operator SMRT said that it had found a crack in the crossing at Changi Airport MRT Station, found during inspection works in the morning. Trains have to be diverted to only one platform and have to travel at a slower speed as they approach the affected crossing.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/slower-train-service-changi-airport-mrt-station-until-jan-21-after-crack-spotted-track|title=Slower train service to Changi Airport MRT Station until Jan 21, after crack spotted on track|date=17 January 2020|work=Today|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Station details and design==\n[[File:Changi Airport MRT Station (EWL - Changi Branch) - Exit A.jpg|thumb|The panes of the glass atria walls seen from Exit A leading to the station|left]]\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{MRT color|East west}}\n|legend =track\n|map=\nuSTR!~MFADEg\\uSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to {{mrts|Expo}}\nuSTR\\uSTR\nudSTRc2!~uvABZg2-\\d!~uv-ABZg3\\udSTRc3\nudABZg+1\\udSTRc14!~d-BS\\udABZg+4\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nuSTR+BSl\\uSTR+BSr\nudSTR\\dBS-\\udSTR\nuENDEe\\uENDEe\n}}\nVarious features have been incorporated into the design to make the station aesthetically pleasing to travellers.<ref name=\"Speech 1\"/> The station is designed by architectural firm [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]], featuring a large interior space and a {{convert|150|metre|ft}} linkbridge spanning over the platform, connecting Terminals 2 and 3 with travellators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sgtrains.com/network-ewl.html|title=East-West Line|website=SGTrains|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Engineering company Meinhardt also provided structural design engineering of the glazing system and the tensioned cable structure of the two atria (approximately 60m long by 20m wide by 36m high each) located at both ends of the station box adjacent to Terminal 2 and 3 of Changi Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meinhardt.com.sg/projects/changi-airport-glass-atria/|title=Changi Airport Glass Atria {{!}} Meinhardt \u2013 Transforming Cities, Shaping the Future|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nChangi Airport station is currently served by the [[East West MRT line|East West line]], which connects to the airport from [[Tanah Merah MRT station|Tanah Merah station]] as a shuttle service. Initially, after the station was first opened, there were through services from [[Boon Lay MRT station|Boon Lay station]] to this station.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boon Lay to Expo: MRT now running|date=20 December 2001|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> However, due to low ridership, the route reverted to being operated as a shuttle service from 22 July that year, with trains from Changi Airport station terminating at Tanah Merah station instead.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Board MRT to airport from Tanah Merah.|date=18 July 2003|work=The Straits Times}}</ref> The first train from Changi Airport station departs at 5.31 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.59 am on Sundays instead, with the last train from the airport departing at 12.06 am.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/changi-airport/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Changi Airport)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> From Tanah Merah station, the first train towards the station departs at 5.20 am on weekdays and Saturdays and 5.47 am on Sundays instead, with the last train towards the airport from Tanah Merah station departing at 11.50 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://journey.smrt.com.sg/journey/station_info/tanah-merah/first-and-last-train/|title=SMRT Journeys (First and last trains from Tanah Merah)|website=journey.smrt.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Headway]] between trains varies from 7 \u2013 9 mins during peak hours, and 12 mins during off-peak hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/|title=Changi Airport MRT Station {{!}} Land Transport Guru|date=2018-01-31|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn the future, the station will be served by the TEL as part of the TEL extension to the airport.<ref name=\"LTMP 2040\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jewel Changi Airport]]\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Changi Airport MRT Station}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smrt.com.sg/Trains/NetworkMap/ChangiAirport.aspx}}\n* [http://blog.smrt.com.sg/?p=159 Official blogsite]\n* [http://www.mynetbizz.com/MRT/To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station/HarbourFront-To-Changi-Airport-MRT-Station.cfm HarbourFront to Changi Airport MRT station route]\n* [http://landtransportguru.net/changi-airport-station/ Changi Airport MRT Station]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|east-west=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Changi Airport MRT station}}\n[[Category:Changi]]\n[[Category:Airport railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2002]]\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) stations]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Singapore]]\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 350268 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 61111 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 403 us -->\n\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 6083007 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73546 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 925 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 338330 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 60129 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 416 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 410717 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 73630 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 861 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Start: injected by Adguard -->\n<!-- Overall parsing time: 321675 us -->\n<!-- Collapse rules timer: 0 us -->\n<!-- Content rules timer: 56806 us -->\n<!-- Css rules timer: 409 us -->\n<!-- End: injected by Adguard -->\n", "name_user": "Lise Hereford", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Changi_Airport_MRT_station"}
{"title_page": "F\u00e1bio Rochemback", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name                 = F\u00e1bio Rochemback\n | image                = \n | fullname             = F\u00e1bio Rochemback\n | birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1981|12|10|df=y}}\n | birth_place          = [[Soledade]], Brazil\n | height               = 1.81 m\n | currentclub          =\n | clubnumber           =\n | position             = [[Midfielder]]\n | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]\n | years1 = 1999\u20132001 | caps1 = 40 | goals1 = 7  | clubs1 = [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]\n | years2 = 2001\u20132005 | caps2 = 45 | goals2 = 3  | clubs2 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n | years3 = 2003\u20132005 | caps3 = 46 | goals3 = 10 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]] (loan)\n | years4 = 2005\u20132008 | caps4 = 68 | goals4 = 5  | clubs4 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n | years5 = 2008\u20132009 | caps5 = 20 | goals5 = 1  | clubs5 = [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]]\n | years6 = 2009\u20132012 | caps6 = 69 | goals6 = 3  | clubs6 = [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]]\n | years7 = 2012\u20132013 | caps7 = 51 | goals7 = 7  | clubs7 = [[Dalian Aerbin]]\n | years8 = 2014      | caps8 =    | goals8 =    | clubs8 = Ipiranga de Passo Fundo\n| totalcaps = 339\n| totalgoals = 36\n | nationalyears1 = 2004 | nationalcaps1 = 6 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | nationalteam1 = [[Brazil Olympic football team|Brazil U23]]\n | nationalyears2 = 2001 | nationalcaps2 = 7 | nationalgoals2 = 0 | nationalteam2 = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]\n}}\n\n'''F\u00e1bio Rochemback''' (born 10 December 1981) is a Brazilian former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\nAt different ends of his career, he represented both ''[[Grenal]]'' rivals of his home state of [[Rio Grande do Sul]]: [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]] and [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]]. He signed for [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] at 19 for \u20ac15 million but struggled,<ref name=jimenez/><ref name=picos/><ref name=mundo/><ref name=sport/> while he reached the [[2005 UEFA Cup Final]] on loan to [[Sporting CP]]. He also spent three years at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] of the [[Premier League]], and played in the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]] for them.\n\nRochemback played seven games for [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], at the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]] and [[2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\n== Club career ==\n\n=== Barcelona ===\nBorn in [[Soledade]], [[Rio Grande do Sul]], Rochemback began his career with nearby [[Sport Club Internacional]] before transferring to [[FC Barcelona]] in July 2001 at the age of 19. The transfer fee was 2.43 billion [[Spanish peseta|pesetas]] in three instalments (\u20ac15 million).<ref name=sport/><ref name=mundo/><ref name=picos>{{cite news |last1=Picos |first1=Sergio |title=De Balones de Oro a pufos: los \u00faltimos brasile\u00f1os del Bar\u00e7a|trans-title=From Ballon d'Or winners to flops: ''Bar\u00e7a''{{'}}s last Brazilians|url=https://as.com/futbol/2017/08/12/primera/1502550623_427482.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Diario AS |date=12 August 2017 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=El Bar\u00e7a presenta a Rochemback|trans-title=''Bar\u00e7a'' present Rochemback  |url=https://as.com/futbol/2001/07/04/mas_futbol/994297186_850215.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Diario AS |date=4 July 2001 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nExpected to be a replacement for the departure of long-serving captain [[Pep Guardiola]], Rochemback played a more physical game than the latter, with a strong shot.<ref name=jimenez>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2017/09/27/primera/1506501533_123725.html|title=Rochemback, la promesa que desilusion\u00f3 a Bar\u00e7a y Sporting|trans-title=Rochemback, the promising player who disappointed ''Bar\u00e7a'' and Sporting|work=Diario AS|date=27 September 2017|language=Spanish|first=Mayca|last=Jim\u00e9nez}}</ref> He has been named as one of the worst players in the club's history, having played at one of their worst periods.<ref name=jimenez/><ref name=picos/><ref name=mundo>{{cite news |last1=Ferragut |first1=Adri\u00e0 |title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 fue de Fabio [''sic''] Rochemback? Fracaso azulgrana, traidor en Brasil y problemas por peleas de gallos|trans-title=What happened to F\u00e1bio Rochemback? ''Azulgrana'' failure, traitor in Brazil and problems for cockfighting |url=https://urbanian.mundodeportivo.com/deportes/12104/que-fue-de-fabio-rochemback-fracaso-azulgrana-traidor-en-brasil-y-problemas-por-peleas-de-gallos |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Mundo Deportivo |date=28 August 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=sport>{{cite news |last1=Bona |first1=German |title=Rochemback, el 'ca\u00f1onero' que desvi\u00f3 su trayectoria|trans-title=Rochemback, the 'gunner' whose career went off|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/barca/rochemback-canonero-que-desvio-trayectoria-6746037 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Sport |date=11 April 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref> In two full seasons at the [[Camp Nou]] he made 68 total appearances and scored four goals, most memorably a long-distance strike as a substitute in a 3\u20131 [[UEFA Champions League]] win away to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 20 November 2001.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lacey |first1=David |title=Reds reel under Barca backlash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/nov/21/championsleague.sport1 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=21 November 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2003, Rochemback was loaned to Portugal's [[Sporting CP]] for a year, as part of the deal that saw [[Ricardo Quaresma]] move in the other direction for \u20ac10 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Quaresma no Barcelona, Rochemback em Alvalade|trans-title=Quaresma to Barcelona, Rochemback to Alvalade|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/sporting/detalhe/quaresma-no-barcelona-rochemback-em-alvalade |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Record |date=8 July 2003 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> In his second season in [[Lisbon]], he helped the club to the final of the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Cup]], scoring a 30-metre free kick in a 2\u20131 win at [[Feyenoord]] in the second leg of the last 16,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sporting's final fantasy alive |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/01a6-0e6cae562cd0-28bddf8d3aa1-1000/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=24 February 2005}}</ref> and wrapped up a 4\u20131 win over [[Newcastle United]] (4\u20132 aggregate) in the second part of the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Michael |title=Sporting blow Newcastle away |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/apr/15/newsstory.sport14 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=15 April 2005}}</ref> In [[2005 UEFA Cup Final|the final]] at the club's own [[Est\u00e1dio Jos\u00e9 Alvalade]] he played the full 90 minutes of a 3\u20131 loss to [[PFC CSKA Moscow]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Matt |title=Abramovich backs winner again as CSKA secure Russian first |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/may/19/match.sportinglisbon |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=19 May 2005}}</ref>\n\n=== Middlesbrough ===\nHaving caught the eye of [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] manager [[Steve McClaren]] during a UEFA Cup game for Sporting earlier in the year, Rochemback signed a five-year deal with the [[Teesside]] club on transfer deadline day of 31 August 2005. The late deal had been jeopardised by financial complications: Sporting were subject to a \u20ac1 million payment to Barcelona if Rochemback did not spend three years on loan at the club, so Middlesbrough agreed to pay this fee as well.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boro's last-gasp Rochemback deal |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/7143609.boros-last-gasp-rochemback-deal/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Northern Echo |date=1 September 2005}}</ref> This transfer is one of those about which the [[2006 allegations of corruption in English football#Stevens report|Stevens inquiry]] report in June 2007 expressed concerns because of the lack of co-operation from agents [[Pini Zahavi]] and [[Barry Silkman]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Transfer probe queries 17 deals |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/6755991.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2007 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Zahavi deals \u2013 the full story can be told |first=David |last=Bond |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2315995/The-Zahavi-deals-the-full-story-can-be-told.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=28 June 2007 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nRochemback made his league debut in a 2\u20131 home win over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 10 September,<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 2\u20131 Arsenal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4210896.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 September 2005 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> and scored his first goal on 11 February 2006 in a 3\u20130 victory against leaders and reigning champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] also at the [[Riverside Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 3\u20130 Chelsea |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4680570.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 February 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> His first [[FA Cup]] goal for Middlesbrough came direct from a free kick, in a 4\u20132 victory over [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in a quarter\u2013final replay on 11 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 4\u20132 Charlton |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/4891500.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 April 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> He also played an important role in Middlesbrough's run to the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]] in a 4\u20131 victory (4\u20133 on aggregate) against [[FC Basel]] in the quarter\u2013final second leg on 6 April, which he was named man of the match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 4\u20131 Basel (agg 4\u20133) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/4875620.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 April 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nRochemback scored a free kick in Middlesbrough's last match of the [[2007\u201308 Premier League]] an 8\u20131 win over [[Manchester City]] on 11 May 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 8\u20131 Man City |first=Chris |last=Bevan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7381794.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Sporting CP ===\nOn 13 May 2008, Rochemback was released from Middlesbrough,<ref name=\"Rochemback shown Boro exit door\">{{cite news |title=Rochemback shown Boro exit door |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/7398544.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> after they rejected the chance to take up a two-year option on his contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rochemback shown Boro exit door |first=Rob |last=Stewart |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2300395/Fabio-Rochemback-to-leave-Middlesbrough.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> He signed a three-year deal to return to Sporting on the same day.<ref name=\"Rochemback shown Boro exit door\"/>\n\n=== Gr\u00eamio ===\nIn August 2009, Rochemback signed a two\u2013year contract with [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] and acquired 30% economic rights for \u20ac928,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sporting.pt/incscp/pdf/investor_relations/ir_ofertaspublicas_prospecto_101210.pdf|title=Oferta p\u00fablica de subscri\u00e7\u00e3o \u2013 Prospecto|trans-title=Public Offer for Subscription \u2013 Prospectus|date=10 December 2010|accessdate=13 January 2011|work=Sporting CP|language=Portuguese|format=pdf }}</ref> Sporting retained 40% economic rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sporting.pt/incscp/pdf/investor_relations/RelatorioContas0910_300910.pdf|title=Relat\u00f3rio e Contas 2009 / 2010 aprovado em Assembleia Geral de 29 de Setembro de 2010|date=30 September 2010|accessdate=9 November 2010|work=Sporting CP| language =Portuguese}}</ref> (However Sporting later announced it sold 90% rights<ref>[http://www.sporting.pt/incscp/pdf/investor_relations/ir_comunicado1_170708.pdf Prospecto de admiss\u00e3o \u00e0 negocia\u00e7\u00e3o no Eurolist by Euronext da Euronext Lisbon]</ref>) In January 2011 he extended his contract to\n31 December 2012.<ref>[http://www.centralesportiva.com.br/noticias.php?codigo=1244240157 Rochemback renova com o Gr\u00eamio at\u00e9 o final de 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120723210923/http://www.centralesportiva.com.br/noticias.php?codigo=1244240157 |date=23 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Dalian ===\nIn January 2012, [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] directors confirmed the transfer of Rochemback to [[Chinese Super League]] club [[Dalian Aerbin]]. He left the club in the end of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.br/noticias/134534-apos-liberacao-de-edinho-rochemback-entra-na-mira-do-fluminense|title=Ap\u00f3s libera\u00e7\u00e3o de Edinho, Rochemback entra na mira do Flu|website=www.foxsports.com.br}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to Brazil ===\nBefore manager [[Renato Ga\u00facho]] signed with [[Fluminense FC|Fluminense]] for the 2014 season, he recommended the signing of Rochemback, who he coached while at Gr\u00eamio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.lance.com.br/deprima/2013/12/27/rochemback-pedido-especial-de-renato-gaucho/?doing_wp_cron=1453896067.2402210235595703125000|title=Rochemback: pedido especial de Renato Ga\u00facho \u2013 De Prima \u2013 LANCE!|date=27 December 2013|publisher=}}</ref> In January 2014, Rochemback was close to sign with [[Sport Club do Recife|Sport]] in a two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/pe/futebol/times/sport/noticia/2014/01/pai-de-fabio-rochemback-diz-que-atleta-esta-perto-de-acertar-com-sport.html|title=Pai de F\u00e1bio Rochemback diz que atleta est\u00e1 perto de acertar com Sport|publisher=}}</ref> The club ended the negotiations due to a change in the financial agreement after a first offer was previously agreed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.br/noticias/137444-sport-recusa-pedida-de-rochemback-que-fica-distante-de-acerto|title=Sport recusa pedida de Rochemback, que fica distante de acerto|website=www.foxsports.com.br}}</ref>\n\nIn June, he joined [[Passo Fundo]] amateur club Ipiranga and won the amateur tournament held by the city in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rdplanalto.com/noticias/7079/ipiranga-conquista-a-taca-do-futebol-amador-em-passo-fundo|title=Ipiranga conquista a ta\u00e7a do futebol amador em Passo Fundo|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onacional.com.br/esporte/53962/ipiranga+e+bicampeao|title=O NACIONAL \u2013 Not\u00edcias de Passo Fundo e regi\u00e3o|first=Parceria Sistemas -|last=www.parcerianet.com.br|website=www.onacional.com.br}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nRochemback earned seven [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], all in competitions in 2001. He made his debut on 31 May in the team's [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]] opener against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], replacing [[V\u00e1gner Rog\u00e9rio Nunes|V\u00e1gner]] at half time in a 2\u20130 win;<ref>{{cite news |title=Brasil joga quatro minutos e vence Camar\u00f5es|trans-title=Brazil play for four minutes and beat Cameroon |url=https://www.terra.com.br/esportes/2001/05/31/025.htm |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Terra |date=31 May 2001 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> he played all five games as the team came fourth. Weeks later, he went to the [[2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] in Colombia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roberts |first1=Mike |title=FC Barcelona and the history of the Copa America |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1066112/fc-barcelona-and-the-history-of-the-copa-america# |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2011, police found birds used for [[cockfighting]] at a building owned by Rochemback in Soledade. In October 2017, he was arrested on further charges of involvement in the blood sport when evidence was found in [[Palmeira das Miss\u00f5es]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gullon |first1=Nick |title=Report former Middlesbrough player Fabio Rochemback arrested in Brazil for alleged cockfighting offences |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/15587247.report-former-middlesbrough-player-fabio-rochemback-arrested-brazil-alleged-cockfighting-offences/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Northern Echo |date=10 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n'''Sporting CP'''\n* [[UEFA Cup]] Runner-up: [[2005 UEFA Cup Final|2004\u201305]]\n\n'''Middlesbrough'''\n* [[UEFA Cup]] Runner-up: [[2006 UEFA Cup Final|2005\u201306]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{NFT|1036}}\n* {{BDFutbol|725}}\n* {{ForaDeJogo|198112100001}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100402071329/http://www.cbf.com.br/php/registro.php?i=138075 CBF] {{in lang|pt}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Brazil squads\n|bg = #FBEC5D\n|fg = #008000\n|list1 =\n{{Brazil squad 2001 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Brazil squad 2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rochemback, Fabio}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Rio Grande do Sul]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazil international footballers]]\n[[Category:2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:2001 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:Sport Club Internacional players]]\n[[Category:Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dalian Yifang F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in China]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name                 = F\u00e1bio Rochemback\n | image                = \n | fullname             = F\u00e1bio Rochemback\n | birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1981|12|10|df=y}}\n | birth_place          = [[Soledade]], Brazil\n | height               = {{height|m=1.81}}\n | currentclub          =\n | clubnumber           =\n | position             = [[Midfielder]]\n | youthyears1   =  | youthclubs1   = [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]\n | years1   = 1999\u20132001  | caps1   = 40  | goals1   = 7   | clubs1   = [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]\n | years2   = 2001\u20132005  | caps2   = 45  | goals2   = 3   | clubs2   = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n | years3   = 2003\u20132005  | caps3   = 46  | goals3   = 10  | clubs3   = \u2192 [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]] (loan)\n | years4   = 2005\u20132008  | caps4   = 68  | goals4   = 5   | clubs4   = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n | years5   = 2008\u20132009  | caps5   = 20  | goals5   = 1   | clubs5   = [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]]\n | years6   = 2009\u20132012  | caps6   = 69  | goals6   = 3   | clubs6   = [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]]\n | years7   = 2012\u20132013  | caps7   = 51  | goals7   = 7   | clubs7   = [[Dalian Aerbin]]\n | years8   = 2014       | caps8   =     | goals8   =     | clubs8   = Ipiranga de Passo Fundo\n | nationalyears1   = 2004  | nationalcaps1   = 6  | nationalgoals1   = 0  | nationalteam1   = [[Brazil Olympic football team|Brazil U23]]\n | nationalyears2   = 2001 | nationalcaps2   = 7  | nationalgoals2   = 0  | nationalteam2   = [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]\n | pcupdate             = 7 November 2013\n | ntupdate             =\n}}\n\n'''F\u00e1bio Rochemback''' (born 10 December 1981) is a Brazilian former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\nAt different ends of his career, he represented both ''[[Grenal]]'' rivals of his home state of [[Rio Grande do Sul]]: [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]] and [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]]. He signed for [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] at 19 for \u20ac15 million but struggled,<ref name=jimenez/><ref name=picos/><ref name=mundo/><ref name=sport/> while he reached the [[2005 UEFA Cup Final]] on loan to [[Sporting CP]]. He also spent three years at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] of the [[Premier League]], and played in the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]] for them.\n\nRochemback played seven games for [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], at the [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]] and [[2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\n== Club career ==\n\n=== Barcelona ===\nBorn in [[Soledade]], [[Rio Grande do Sul]], Rochemback began his career with nearby [[Sport Club Internacional]] before transferring to [[FC Barcelona]] in July 2001 at the age of 19. The transfer fee was 2.43 billion [[Spanish peseta|pesetas]] in three instalments (\u20ac15 million).<ref name=sport/><ref name=mundo/><ref name=picos>{{cite news |last1=Picos |first1=Sergio |title=De Balones de Oro a pufos: los \u00faltimos brasile\u00f1os del Bar\u00e7a|trans-title=From Ballon d'Or winners to flops: ''Bar\u00e7a''{{'}}s last Brazilians|url=https://as.com/futbol/2017/08/12/primera/1502550623_427482.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Diario AS |date=12 August 2017 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=El Bar\u00e7a presenta a Rochemback|trans-title=''Bar\u00e7a'' present Rochemback  |url=https://as.com/futbol/2001/07/04/mas_futbol/994297186_850215.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Diario AS |date=4 July 2001 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nExpected to be a replacement for the departure of long-serving captain [[Pep Guardiola]], Rochemback played a more physical game than the latter, with a strong shot.<ref name=jimenez>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2017/09/27/primera/1506501533_123725.html|title=Rochemback, la promesa que desilusion\u00f3 a Bar\u00e7a y Sporting|trans-title=Rochemback, the promising player who disappointed ''Bar\u00e7a'' and Sporting|work=Diario AS|date=27 September 2017|language=Spanish|first=Mayca|last=Jim\u00e9nez}}</ref> He has been named as one of the worst players in the club's history, having played at one of their worst periods.<ref name=jimenez/><ref name=picos/><ref name=mundo>{{cite news |last1=Ferragut |first1=Adri\u00e0 |title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 fue de Fabio [''sic''] Rochemback? Fracaso azulgrana, traidor en Brasil y problemas por peleas de gallos|trans-title=What happened to F\u00e1bio Rochemback? ''Azulgrana'' failure, traitor in Brazil and problems for cockfighting |url=https://urbanian.mundodeportivo.com/deportes/12104/que-fue-de-fabio-rochemback-fracaso-azulgrana-traidor-en-brasil-y-problemas-por-peleas-de-gallos |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Mundo Deportivo |date=28 August 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=sport>{{cite news |last1=Bona |first1=German |title=Rochemback, el 'ca\u00f1onero' que desvi\u00f3 su trayectoria|trans-title=Rochemback, the 'gunner' whose career went off|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/barca/rochemback-canonero-que-desvio-trayectoria-6746037 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Sport |date=11 April 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref> In two full seasons at the [[Camp Nou]] he made 68 total appearances and scored four goals, most memorably a long-distance strike as a substitute in a 3\u20131 [[UEFA Champions League]] win away to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 20 November 2001.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lacey |first1=David |title=Reds reel under Barca backlash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/nov/21/championsleague.sport1 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=21 November 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2003, Rochemback was loaned to Portugal's [[Sporting CP]] for a year, as part of the deal that saw [[Ricardo Quaresma]] move in the other direction for \u20ac10 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Quaresma no Barcelona, Rochemback em Alvalade|trans-title=Quaresma to Barcelona, Rochemback to Alvalade|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/sporting/detalhe/quaresma-no-barcelona-rochemback-em-alvalade |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Record |date=8 July 2003 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> In his second season in [[Lisbon]], he helped the club to the final of the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Cup]], scoring a 30-metre free kick in a 2\u20131 win at [[Feyenoord]] in the second leg of the last 16,<ref>{{cite news |title=Sporting's final fantasy alive |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/01a6-0e6cae562cd0-28bddf8d3aa1-1000/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=24 February 2005}}</ref> and wrapped up a 4\u20131 win over [[Newcastle United]] (4\u20132 aggregate) in the second part of the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Michael |title=Sporting blow Newcastle away |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/apr/15/newsstory.sport14 |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=15 April 2005}}</ref> In [[2005 UEFA Cup Final|the final]] at the club's own [[Est\u00e1dio Jos\u00e9 Alvalade]] he played the full 90 minutes of a 3\u20131 loss to [[PFC CSKA Moscow]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Matt |title=Abramovich backs winner again as CSKA secure Russian first |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/may/19/match.sportinglisbon |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=19 May 2005}}</ref>\n\n=== Middlesbrough ===\nHaving caught the eye of [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] manager [[Steve McClaren]] during a UEFA Cup game for Sporting earlier in the year, Rochemback signed a five-year deal with the [[Teesside]] club on transfer deadline day of 31 August 2005. The late deal had been jeopardised by financial complications: Sporting were subject to a \u20ac1 million payment to Barcelona if Rochemback did not spend three years on loan at the club, so Middlesbrough agreed to pay this fee as well.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boro's last-gasp Rochemback deal |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/7143609.boros-last-gasp-rochemback-deal/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Northern Echo |date=1 September 2005}}</ref> This transfer is one of those about which the [[2006 allegations of corruption in English football#Stevens report|Stevens inquiry]] report in June 2007 expressed concerns because of the lack of co-operation from agents [[Pini Zahavi]] and [[Barry Silkman]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Transfer probe queries 17 deals |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/6755991.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 June 2007 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Zahavi deals \u2013 the full story can be told |first=David |last=Bond |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2315995/The-Zahavi-deals-the-full-story-can-be-told.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=28 June 2007 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nRochemback made his league debut in a 2\u20131 home win over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 10 September,<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 2\u20131 Arsenal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4210896.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 September 2005 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> and scored his first goal on 11 February 2006 in a 3\u20130 victory against leaders and reigning champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] also at the [[Riverside Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 3\u20130 Chelsea |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4680570.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 February 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> His first [[FA Cup]] goal for Middlesbrough came direct from a free kick, in a 4\u20132 victory over [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in a quarter\u2013final replay on 11 April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 4\u20132 Charlton |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/4891500.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 April 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> He also played an important role in Middlesbrough's run to the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]] in a 4\u20131 victory (4\u20133 on aggregate) against [[FC Basel]] in the quarter\u2013final second leg on 6 April, which he was named man of the match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 4\u20131 Basel (agg 4\u20133) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/4875620.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 April 2006 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nRochemback scored a free kick in Middlesbrough's last match of the [[2007\u201308 Premier League]] an 8\u20131 win over [[Manchester City]] on 11 May 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough 8\u20131 Man City |first=Chris |last=Bevan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7381794.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Sporting CP ===\nOn 13 May 2008, Rochemback was released from Middlesbrough,<ref name=\"Rochemback shown Boro exit door\">{{cite news |title=Rochemback shown Boro exit door |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/7398544.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> after they rejected the chance to take up a two-year option on his contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rochemback shown Boro exit door |first=Rob |last=Stewart |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2300395/Fabio-Rochemback-to-leave-Middlesbrough.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 May 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref> He signed a three-year deal to return to Sporting on the same day.<ref name=\"Rochemback shown Boro exit door\"/>\n\n=== Gr\u00eamio ===\nIn August 2009, Rochemback signed a two\u2013year contract with [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] and acquired 30% economic rights for \u20ac928,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sporting.pt/incscp/pdf/investor_relations/ir_ofertaspublicas_prospecto_101210.pdf|title=Oferta p\u00fablica de subscri\u00e7\u00e3o \u2013 Prospecto|trans-title=Public Offer for Subscription \u2013 Prospectus|date=10 December 2010|accessdate=13 January 2011|work=Sporting CP|language=Portuguese|format=pdf }}</ref> Sporting retained 40% economic rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sporting.pt/incscp/pdf/investor_relations/RelatorioContas0910_300910.pdf|title=Relat\u00f3rio e Contas 2009 / 2010 aprovado em Assembleia Geral de 29 de Setembro de 2010|date=30 September 2010|accessdate=9 November 2010|work=Sporting CP| language =Portuguese}}</ref> (However Sporting later announced it sold 90% rights<ref>[http://www.sporting.pt/incscp/pdf/investor_relations/ir_comunicado1_170708.pdf Prospecto de admiss\u00e3o \u00e0 negocia\u00e7\u00e3o no Eurolist by Euronext da Euronext Lisbon]</ref>) In January 2011 he extended his contract to\n31 December 2012.<ref>[http://www.centralesportiva.com.br/noticias.php?codigo=1244240157 Rochemback renova com o Gr\u00eamio at\u00e9 o final de 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120723210923/http://www.centralesportiva.com.br/noticias.php?codigo=1244240157 |date=23 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Dalian ===\nIn January 2012, [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] directors confirmed the transfer of Rochemback to [[Chinese Super League]] club [[Dalian Aerbin]]. He left the club in the end of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.br/noticias/134534-apos-liberacao-de-edinho-rochemback-entra-na-mira-do-fluminense|title=Ap\u00f3s libera\u00e7\u00e3o de Edinho, Rochemback entra na mira do Flu|website=www.foxsports.com.br}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to Brazil ===\nBefore manager [[Renato Ga\u00facho]] signed with [[Fluminense FC|Fluminense]] for the 2014 season, he recommended the signing of Rochemback, who he coached while at Gr\u00eamio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.lance.com.br/deprima/2013/12/27/rochemback-pedido-especial-de-renato-gaucho/?doing_wp_cron=1453896067.2402210235595703125000|title=Rochemback: pedido especial de Renato Ga\u00facho \u2013 De Prima \u2013 LANCE!|date=27 December 2013|publisher=}}</ref> In January 2014, Rochemback was close to sign with [[Sport Club do Recife|Sport]] in a two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/pe/futebol/times/sport/noticia/2014/01/pai-de-fabio-rochemback-diz-que-atleta-esta-perto-de-acertar-com-sport.html|title=Pai de F\u00e1bio Rochemback diz que atleta est\u00e1 perto de acertar com Sport|publisher=}}</ref> The club ended the negotiations due to a change in the financial agreement after a first offer was previously agreed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.br/noticias/137444-sport-recusa-pedida-de-rochemback-que-fica-distante-de-acerto|title=Sport recusa pedida de Rochemback, que fica distante de acerto|website=www.foxsports.com.br}}</ref>\n\nIn June, he joined [[Passo Fundo]] amateur club Ipiranga and won the amateur tournament held by the city in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rdplanalto.com/noticias/7079/ipiranga-conquista-a-taca-do-futebol-amador-em-passo-fundo|title=Ipiranga conquista a ta\u00e7a do futebol amador em Passo Fundo|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onacional.com.br/esporte/53962/ipiranga+e+bicampeao|title=O NACIONAL \u2013 Not\u00edcias de Passo Fundo e regi\u00e3o|first=Parceria Sistemas -|last=www.parcerianet.com.br|website=www.onacional.com.br}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nRochemback earned seven [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], all in competitions in 2001. He made his debut on 31 May in the team's [[2001 FIFA Confederations Cup]] opener against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], replacing [[V\u00e1gner Rog\u00e9rio Nunes|V\u00e1gner]] at half time in a 2\u20130 win;<ref>{{cite news |title=Brasil joga quatro minutos e vence Camar\u00f5es|trans-title=Brazil play for four minutes and beat Cameroon |url=https://www.terra.com.br/esportes/2001/05/31/025.htm |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Terra |date=31 May 2001 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> he played all five games as the team came fourth. Weeks later, he went to the [[2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] in Colombia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roberts |first1=Mike |title=FC Barcelona and the history of the Copa America |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1066112/fc-barcelona-and-the-history-of-the-copa-america# |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2011, police found birds used for [[cockfighting]] at a building owned by Rochemback in Soledade. In October 2017, he was arrested on further charges of involvement in the blood sport when evidence was found in [[Palmeira das Miss\u00f5es]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gullon |first1=Nick |title=Report former Middlesbrough player Fabio Rochemback arrested in Brazil for alleged cockfighting offences |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/15587247.report-former-middlesbrough-player-fabio-rochemback-arrested-brazil-alleged-cockfighting-offences/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Northern Echo |date=10 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n;Sporting CP\n* [[UEFA Cup]] Runner-up: [[2005 UEFA Cup Final|2004\u201305]]\n\n;Middlesbrough\n* [[UEFA Cup]] Runner-up: [[2006 UEFA Cup Final|2005\u201306]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{NFT player|pid=1036}}\n* [https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j725.html Rochemback] at BDFutbol\n* [https://www.foradejogo.net/player.php?player=198112100001 Rochemback] at ForaDeJogo\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090930191542/http://www.portugoal.net/index.php/player-profiles/124-players-p-r/149-player-profile-fabio-rochemback Fabio Rochemback PortuGOAL profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100402071329/http://www.cbf.com.br/php/registro.php?i=138075 CBF] {{in lang|pt}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Brazil squads\n|bg = #FBEC5D\n|fg = #008000\n|list1 =\n{{Brazil squad 2001 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Brazil squad 2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rochemback, Fabio}}\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazil international footballers]]\n[[Category:2001 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:2001 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:Sport Club Internacional players]]\n[[Category:Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dalian Yifang F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in China]]\n[[Category:People from Rio Grande do Sul]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add totalcaps and totalgoals. Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%A1bio_Rochemback"}
{"title_page": "Astro (South Korean band)", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean boy band}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Astro\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Astro at \"Dream Part. 01\" Showcase.png\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Astro in May 2017. From left to right: Jinjin, Sanha, Eunwoo, MJ, Moonbin and Rocky\n| origin           = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| genre            = [[K-pop]]\n| years_active     = 2016\u2013present\n| label            = [[Fantagio]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.fantagio.kr/musicians/\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c/}}\n| current_members  = *MJ\n*JinJin\n*[[Cha Eun-woo]]\n*[[Moon Bin]]\n*Rocky\n*Yoon San-ha\n}}\n'''Astro''' ({{Korean|\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c}}) is a South Korean [[boy band]] formed by [[Fantagio]] that debuted in '''2016.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fantagio.kr/groups/|title=Fantagio Groups List|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The group is composed of six members: '''MJ, [[Cha Eun-woo]], [[Moon Bin|Moonbin]], Jinjin, Rocky''' and '''Yoon Sanha.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.naver.com/search.naver?sm=mtb_pcv&where=nexearch&query=%EC%95%84%EC%8A%A4%ED%8A%B8%EB%A1%9C|title=Official Astro Naver Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> They debuted with the single '''\"Hide & Seek\"''' from their debut EP ''[[Spring Up]]'', and were subsequently named by '''''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' as one of the best new [[K-pop]] groups of 2016.'''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Herman|first1=Tamar|title=10 Best New K-Pop Groups In 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2016/7625235/best-k-pop-debuts-2016|accessdate=6 July 2017|agency=Billboard|date=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Pre-debut===\nThe members of Astro were known as iTeen Boys while training as part of Fantagio iTeen, a rookie talent development program under the management agency [[Fantagio]]. The group's name and members were announced in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last=Yoon|first=Gi-baek|script-title=ko:\ud310\ud0c0\uc9c0\uc624 \ub274 \ubcf4\uc774\uadf8\ub8f9, \ud300\uba85 '\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c' \ud655\uc815|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=396&aid=0000335291|accessdate=2017-12-22|agency=Sports World|publisher=Sports World|date=2015-08-14|language=ko}}</ref> That month, they starred in a web drama series titled ''To Be Continued''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elizabeth|first=Hailie|title=ASTRO Kick Off Debut Promotions With New Web Drama 'To Be Continued'|url=http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/232419/astro-kpop-to-be-continued.htm|accessdate=2017-12-22|agency=KpopStarz|publisher=KpopStarz.com|date=2015-08-19}}</ref> The web drama featured the members as themselves, as well as [[Kim Sae-ron]], [[Seo Kang-joon]], and [[Hello Venus]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Seo Kang Jun to act alongside rookie boy group ASTRO and Kim Sae Ron in 'To Be Continued'|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2015/08/seo-kang-jun-to-act-alongside-rookie-boy-group-astro-and-kim-sae-ron-in-to-be-continued|accessdate=2017-12-22|agency=Allkpop|publisher=Allkpop|date=2015-08-17}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Astro starred in their own reality show, ''Astro OK! Ready'', which was aired on [[MBC Every1]] at 7PM KST.<ref>{{cite news|title=Just Before Their Debut, Astro To Star In A New Reality Show|url=http://officiallykmusic.com/just-before-their-debut-astro-to-star-in-a-new-reality-show/|accessdate=2017-12-22|agency=Officially Kmusic|publisher=Officially Kmusic|date=2016-01-19}}</ref>\n\n===2016: Debut with ''Spring Up'', ''Summer Vibes'' and ''Autumn Story''===\nAstro's debut extended play ''[[Spring Up]],'' was released on February 23, 2016, featuring title track \"Hide & Seek\".<ref name=\"spring up\">{{cite web|url=http://music.naver.com/album/index.nhn?albumId=619875|title=Spring Up|work=[[Naver]] Music|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref> The group held a debut showcase where they announced their official fan club name Aroha (an abbreviation for \"Astro hearts all fans\").<ref>{{cite news|title=Astro Announces Their Fandom Name At Their Debut Showcase!|url=http://officiallykmusic.com/astro-announces-their-fandom-name-at-their-debut-showcase/|accessdate=26 October 2016|agency=Officially Kmusic|publisher=Officially Kmusic|date=26 February 2016}}</ref> Within a week of its release, ''Spring Up'' reached #6 on the [[Billboard chart|Billboard World Albums Chart]] in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/world-albums/2016-03-12|title=World Albums|date=2016-03-12|work=[[Billboard chart|Billboard]]|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref> as well as #4 on the [[Gaon Music Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=09&hitYear=2016&termGbn=week |title=Spring Up on Gaon Chart |work=Gaon Music Chart |publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association |language=ko}}</ref> On February 25, the group released the music video for \"Cat's Eye\", containing clips from their web series ''To Be Continued''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allkpop.com/article/2016/02/check-out-astros-talent-show-themed-mv-for-cats-eye |title= Check out ASTRO's talent-show-themed MV for 'Cat's Eye'! |work=Allkpop |date=25 February 2016|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> In March, 6 the group was the only Korean act invited to the LeTV Entertainment Awards in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2016/03/astro-is-exclusively-invited-to-letv-entertainment-awards-in-china|title=ASTRO is exclusively invited to 'Letv Entertainment Awards' in China!|work=Allkpop|date=2016-03-22|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref>\n\nTheir second extended play ''[[Summer Vibes]]'' was released on July 1 with the title track \"Breathless\", with a music video featuring former [[I.O.I]] member and current [[Weki Meki]] labelmate [[Choi Yoo-jung (singer)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2016/06/astro-are-breathless-in-full-mv|title=ASTRO are 'Breathless' in full MV!|publisher=Allkpop|date=2016-06-30|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref> The album peaked at #6 on the Billboard World Albums Chart and #21 on the [[Billboard chart|Billboard World Digital Songs Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7438251/astro-summer-vibes-world-albums-breathless |title=ASTRO Earn 2nd Top 10 Entry on World Albums With 'Summer Vibes'|work=Billboard|date=2016-07-13|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref>\n\nAstro performed at [[Staples Center]] in Los Angeles on July 31 for [[KCON (music festival)|KCON 2016]].<ref name=\"kcl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7378226/dean-astro-added-kcon-usa-lineup|title=DEAN, ASTRO Added to KCON USA Lineup|work=Billboard|date=2016-05-20|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref> They held their first solo concert on August 27\u201328 at the KEPCO Art Center in Seoul.<ref>{{cite news|last=Han|first=In-gu|script-title=ko:\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c, \ub370\ubdd4 5\uac1c\uc6d4\ub9cc\uc5d0 \ub2e8\ub3c5\ucf58\uc11c\ud2b8 \uac1c\ucd5c|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=009&aid=0003770629|agency=\ub9e4\uc77c\uacbd\uc81c|publisher=\ub9e4\uc77c\uacbd\uc81c|date=2016-07-20|accessdate=2017-12-22|language=ko}}</ref> The group also held showcases in Japan, Indonesia, and Thailand throughout the months of October and November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpopmap.com/astro-meet-international-fans-1st-asia-concert-tour/|title=ASTRO to Meet International Fans at 1st Asia Concert Tour|work=Kpopmap|date=2016-08-18|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2016/08/astro-to-hold-their-first-asia-showcase-in-thailand|title=ASTRO to hold their first Asia showcase in Thailand!|work=Allkpop|date=2016-08-03|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref>\n\nAstro's third extended play ''[[Autumn Story (EP)|Autumn Story]]'', was released on November 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/astro-confirms-november-comeback-reveals-upcoming-concept|title=ASTRO Looks Lovingly Sweet In Teaser Images For \"Autumn Story\"|work=Soompi|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref> The music video features labelmate Sei of [[Weki Meki]].\n\n=== 2017: ''Winter Dream'', ''Dream Part.01'', first tour and ''Dream Part.02''===\nOn February 22, 2017, Astro released ''Winter Dream'', featuring title track \"Should Have Held On To You (Again)\". Despite the album being the final piece to the groups seasonal album concept, it was not promoted on music shows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/949349wpp/astro-beautiful-white-new-teasers-special-album-winter-dream|title=Update: ASTRO Shares Highlight Medley For \"Winter Dream\"|date=Feb 13, 2017|website=Soompi|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, Astro released their fourth extended play ''[[Dream Part.01]]'', featuring title track \"Baby\".<ref>{{cite news|title=ASTRO bring fans into their store with \"Baby\"|url=http://www.onestopkpop.com/astro-bring-fans-into-their-store-with-baby/|accessdate=2017-12-22|work=One Stop K-Pop|date=2017-05-29}}</ref> The group held their first tour, titled \"The 1st ASTROAD\", from July 15\u2013August 29, with dates in Seoul, Osaka, and Tokyo.<ref>{{cite news|title=ASTRO to hold first ever solo concert in July|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2017/05/astro-to-hold-first-ever-solo-concert-in-july|accessdate=2017-12-22|work=Allkpop|date=2017-05-29}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, Astro released their fifth extended play ''Dream Part.02'' featuring the title track \"Crazy Sexy Cool\"''.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8022233/astro-crazy-sexy-love-video-dream-pt-02-ep|title=Astro Returns With Smooth New 'Crazy Sexy Cool' Video|work=Billboard|date=2017-01-11|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref> On January 10, 2018, the group released a limited edition of their album ''Dream Part.02 'Wish''' version which sold out all 10,000 copies in pre-orders alone. The special album contains a poem by member Eunwoo, a hidden 'thanks to', and polaroid photos which the members took themselves.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.allkpop.com/article/2018/01/astro-sell-out-all-10000-copies-of-their-limited-version-dream-part02|title=ASTRO sell out all 10,000 copies of their limited version 'Dream Part.02' {{!}} allkpop.com|work=Allkpop|access-date=2018-01-10}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018: Global Fanmeeting Tour, ''Rise Up,'' and Group Hiatus===\nThroughout February and March 2018, Astro embarked on a fan meeting world tour visiting cities in countries such as the United States, Canada, South Korea, Japan, and Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kpopmap.com/2018-astro-global-fan-meeting-japan-thailand-dates/|title=2018 ASTRO Global Fan Meeting - Japan & Thailand Dates \u2022 Kpopmap|date=2018-02-28|website=Kpopmap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2018, Astro released ''Rise Up'' featuring title track \"Always You\". The album was not promoted on music programs due to internal issues at their label, Fantagio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8482591/astro-k-pop-boy-band-talks-always-you-single-hiatus|title=K-Pop Boy Band Astro Talks 'Always You' Single, Artistry & Hiatus|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> Despite not being able to promote in their home country the group toured cities such as Nagoya, Osaka, and Tokyo in their \"ASTROAD II in Japan\" tour throughout the month of August, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kpopmap.com/astro-to-hold-astroad-ii-in-japan-this-summer/|title=ASTRO To Hold \"ASTROAD II In Japan\" This Summer \u2022 Kpopmap|date=2018-06-22|website=Kpopmap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019: ''All Light,'' ''Venus,'' ''Blue Flame,'' and Moon Bin's Hiatus===\nOn January 16, 2019, they released their first full-length album, the first album release in general following their 8 month period hiatus, ''[[All Light]].'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8493899/astro-all-night-video|title=Astro Spends 'All Night' Among the Flowers in New Video: Watch|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> To further promote their first full-length album the group announced \"The 2nd ASTROAD Tour\", which included cities across Asia and North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1295759wpp/astro-announces-dates-locations-2nd-world-tour|title=ASTRO Announces Dates + Locations For 2nd World Tour|date=Jan 21, 2019|website=Soompi|language=en|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> On January 21, the label Fantagio announced four US shows following their 2nd Tapei Tour, to conclude with further tour dates in Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8494287/k-pop-boy-band-astro-world-tour-north-america-dates|title=K-Pop Boy Band ASTRO Set World Tour|date=January 22, 2019|website=Billboard|language=en|access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, Astro gained their first music show award during promotions for their release \u201cAll Night\" on the SBS MTV music program [[The Show (South Korean TV series)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1300100wpp/watch-astro-tears-up-as-they-receive-1st-ever-win-on-the-show-with-all-night-performances-by-wjsn-roh-tae-hyun-and-more|title=Watch: ASTRO Tears Up As They Receive 1st Ever Win On \u201cThe Show\u201d With \u201cAll Night\u201d; Performances By WJSN, Roh Tae Hyun, And More|date=January 29, 2019|work=Soompi|language=en-US|access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>. \n\nOn April 3, Astro released their Japan debut EP, ''Venus'' featuring three original Japanese tracks along with three Japanese versions of their Korean singles \"Baby\", \"Always You\", and \"All Night\". The album garnered a successful debut, debuting #2 on the daily album chart of Japan's largest music site [[Oricon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1315021wpp/astro-makes-successful-debut-in-japan-as-venus-grabs-no-2-on-oricons-daily-album-chart|title=ASTRO Makes Successful Debut In Japan As \"Venus\" Grabs No. 2 On Oricon\u2019s Daily Album Chart|date=Apr 4, 2019|website=Soompi|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref>\n\nOn November 12, Fantagio Music announced that Astro's member Moonbin would be going on a hiatus to recover from health issues and focus on his treatment<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://koogle.tv/media/news/astros-moonbin-to-take-break-due-to-health-issues/|title=ASTRO's Moonbin to take break due to health issues!|last=|first=|date=November 12, 2019|work=KoogleTV|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, Astro released their sixth extended play ''Blue Flame''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/now/article/609/0000198107|title=\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c \uce21 \u201c11\uc6d4 20\uc77c \ubbf8\ub2c8 6\uc9d1 \ucef4\ubc31, \uc0c9\ub2e4\ub978 \ubaa8\uc2b5 \ubcf4\uc5ec\uc904\uac83\u201d(\uacf5\uc2dd)|date=2019-11-05|website=news.naver.com|language=ko|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> Moonbin focused on recovery from physical health concerns, allowing him to take a break from group promotions as parts were re-distributed temporarily to other members. Despite this, he participated in the album and appeared in the music video for Blue Flame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1365201wpp/astros-moonbin-to-take-hiatus-due-to-health-concerns|title=ASTRO\u2019s Moonbin To Take Hiatus Due To Health Concerns|last=|first=|date=November 12, 2019|work=Soompi|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020: ''One n Only'' ===\nOn '''February 23''' , Astro released special single album One n Only for their 4th anniversary debut . This album was specially crafted for their fans AROHA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/468/0000629631|title=\uc544\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub85c, \uc624\ub298(23\uc77c) \ub370\ubdd4 4\uc8fc\ub144 \uae30\ub150 \uc2a4\ud398\uc15c \uc2f1\uae00 'ONE&ONLY' \ubc1c\ub9e4|date=2020-02-23|website=news.naver.com|language=ko|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n*MJ ({{Korean|hangul=\uc5e0\uc81c\uc774}})\n*JinJin ({{Korean|hangul=\uc9c4\uc9c4}})\n*[[Cha Eun-woo]] ({{Korean|hangul=\ucc28\uc740\uc6b0}})\n*Moon Bin ({{Korean|hangul=\ubb38\ube48}})\n*Rocky ({{Korean|hangul=\ub77c\ud0a4}})\n*Yoon San-ha ({{Korean|hangul=\uc724\uc0b0\ud558}})\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected details and chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:8em;\"|Title\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"|Details\n!colspan=\"3\"| Peak chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"|Sales\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Gaon Music Chart|KOR]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=03&hitYear=2019&termGbn=week|title=All Light \u2013 Week 3, 2019|website=[[Gaon Music Chart|Gaon Chart]]|language=ko|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Oricon Albums Chart|JPN]]<br><ref name=\"All Light JPN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2019-02-25/p/2/ |script-title=ja:\u9031\u9593\u3000CD\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 2019\u5e7402\u670811\u65e5\uff5e2019\u5e7402\u670817\u65e5 |trans-title=CD album weekly ranking from February 11, 2019 to February 17, 2019 |publisher=Oricon |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%\"|[[Billboard charts#Albums|US<br>{{small|World}}]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/astro/chart-history/world-albums|title=Astro Chart History: World Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| ''[[All Light]]''\n|\n*Released: January 16, 2019 {{small|(KOR)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2019/01/732_261553.html|title